                    Colonies.
                </ab>
                
                <ab>
                    1st Office
                </ab>
                
                <ab>
                    nomination of Mr.
                    Armand as
                    consul of the United States
                    in goreé, Dakar.
                </ab>
                
                <ab>
                    Paris, June 24/84 1884.
                </ab>
                
                <ab>
                    The U.S. of State to Mr.
                    governor of Senegal and dependents <unclear/>
                </ab>
                
                <p>
                    Mister governor, <del>Mr.</del>
                    <del>le president of the council, Minister of </del>
                    <del>Foreign Affairs, has just informed</del>
                    <del>me, and</del> I have the honnor of 
                    informing you that Mr. Charles Armand
                    has just been named vice-consul
                    of the United States in gorée-Dakar.
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    I urge you to take the
                    necessary measures so that this
                    officer is admitted to free exercise
                    of his duties, at least unless
                    you have an objection
                    to raise against his nomination.
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    It is natural that in his
                    quality of a french citizen, Mr.
                    Armand cannot claim
                    the title of vice-consul in order to
                    avoid any obligations
                    imposed by the french laws.
                    
                    R LOD.
                </p>
                
